<h2 id="I-was-sick"><strong>I was sick</strong><a class="anchor-link" href="#I-was-sick"> </a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>It's April, you're at home complying with lockdown measures and helping "flatten the curve". While getting your dinner ready you suddenly have a thought: what if that cold, low grade fever, or slight cough you had a few weeks or months back was actually COVID-19 and you were simply part of the 80% that show minor symptoms?</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>If only there was a simple blood test that could definitively tell you, right?</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Was-it-COVID?"><strong>Was it COVID?</strong><a class="anchor-link" href="#Was-it-COVID?"> </a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>As it turns out, these tests exist.</p>
<p>When someone is infected by the virus their immune system will develop a response and produce antibodies that target the intruder (these antibodies take 1-3 weeks to become visible in blood <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/lab/serology-testing.html" title="CDC Serology Testing">1</a>). A serology or antibody test is simply a test that is able to detect the presence of these antibodies in your blood.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now, in a stroke of luck, you somehow managed to aquire 4 of these antibody tests, 2 each from 2 different laboratories.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Testing-and-intepreting-the-results"><strong>Testing and intepreting the results</strong><a class="anchor-link" href="#Testing-and-intepreting-the-results"> </a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Great, you'll soon know if you've had COVID-19 and are now immune... or not.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>After taking the first 2 tests from the first laboratory, good news! Both come back positive.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Delighted that you are now immune, you pop open the Champagne, but out of an incessant need to be reassured, you decide to take the other 2 tests from the other laboratory. After a couple glasses, the results are in both of these 2 other tests turn out negative.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>You may think this is an outlandish possibility but it is not, and it is exactly what happened to Dr. Antevy <a href="https://twitter.com/HandtevyMD/status/1245832946612711424?s=20">Link to tweet</a></p>
<p>You can see he uses two antibody tests from one manufacturer, and two other tests froma  different manufacturer.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>So you're back to square one seemingly, or are you? While contradicting themselves, these tests offer new information, maybe we can use it somehow.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>What if like in the case of our Doctor, 2 positives and 2 negatives with different sensitivity and specificity ? Let's have a look</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">test_results</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">specificity</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mf">99.1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">99.1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">98.7</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">98.7</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">sensitivity</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mf">93.7</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">93.7</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">98.8</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">98.8</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
